        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.30.9-10_0001a" />
                
                
                
                <opener>
                <dateline>Skyrim, 10-22-'60</dateline>
                
                
                
                <salute>Dear Slade <hi rend="underline">and</hi> Nita:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Well, as you see, I'm here! Everything is fine, and I'm richer for the memories I have of my days with you there. <hi rend="underline">You are very dear</hi>.</p>
                
                <p>We reached St. Louis a bit late, and the waiting for the Ozark plane was <hi rend="underline">not</hi> trying. Alice, Lyn, and Erica were waiting for me at the airport. We were about 40 minutes late.</p> 
                
                <p>I'm judge in the poetry contest <del/> of The Poetry Society of Texas again
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4c.30.9-10_0001b"/>
                    <fw type="authorial">-2-</fw>
                    <fw type="curatorial"><del/></fw>
                    
                    this year (the narrative section only), and I've just chosen the first ten best ones as I see them. Four of these are really good, the other six not at all bad. I've judged for the Texas Society a number of times. Once I gave first to a little masterpiece of a ballad <del>on</del> about an old buckaroo. (It got into Readers' Digest). The deadline this time was Oct. 20, and I reached home on the 21st! So I hurried with the reading.</p> 
                
                <fw type="curatorial">9</fw>
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.30.9-10_0002a"/>
                <fw type="authorial">-3-</fw>
                
                <p>How I do love to think of that beautiful country, and you in it! No fine colors here, except an occasional but rare hard maple. They had a frost &amp; a hard freeze while I was with you. It came <choice><sic>afer</sic><corr>after</corr></choice> that hard rain (an all-night, slow rain of about 2 inches.) My wheat is coming up, and I'll be rich and despised when I harvest my crop next June!</p> 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4c.30.9-10_0002b"/>
                <fw type="authorial">-4-</fw>
                <fw type="curatorial"><del/></fw>
                
                <p>I <hi rend="underline">do</hi> hope I left <hi rend="underline">some</hi> pleasant memory among those who were in my classes or in the Olin audience. (I know it was so in <hi rend="caps">N. Y.</hi> City)</p> 
               
                <p>Yo-Yo was very happy to see me!! They told her I was coming, and she jumped up &amp; down, barking and whining. I wonder if she 
                    <hi rend="underline">did</hi> understand.</p> 
                
                <p>We have cool but golden weather, and I fancy it's the same with you.</p>
                
                <p>Oh, those enchanted nights!</p> 
                <closer>
                <salute>Love,</salute> 
                <signed>John N.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">10</fw>
            </div1>
        </body>
        
